<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note91" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref91
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">91</A>
Sir William Ramsay (<I>Journal of Hellenic Studies</I> 1918,


<A ID="p431x"></A>vol. 38, pp148 ff.) argues that "Mên" is a grecized form for the Anatolian "Manes," the native god of the land of Ouramma; and "Manes Ourammos was Hellenized as Zeus Ouruda-menos or Euruda-menos." See also
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.283766/2015.283766.The-Social#page/n333/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
M. Rostovtzeff, <I>Social and Economic History of the Roman Empire</I>, p238</A>, and
	<A HREF="
http://dagr.univ-tlse2.fr/feuilleter/tome_3/partie_2/page_515
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Daremberg et Saglio, <I>Dict. Antiq.</I>, <I>s.v.</I> "Lunus."
	</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note92" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">92</A>
"Ascaënus" (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἀσκαηνός</SPAN>) is the regular spelling of the word, the spelling found in hundreds of inscriptions, whereas Ascaeus (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἀσκαῖος</SPAN>) has been found in only two inscriptions, according to Professor David M. Robinson. On this temple, see Sir W. M. Ramsay's "Excavations at Pisidian Antioch in 1912," <I>The Athenaeum</I>, London, March 8, Aug. 31, and Sept. 7, 1913.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note93" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref93
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">93</A>
Note that Strabo, both here and in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12H*.html#8.14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
12.8.14</A>, refers to this Antioch as "the Antioch near Pisidia," not as "Pisidian Antioch," the appellation now in common use. Neither does Artemidorus (lived about 100 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>), as quoted by Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12G*.html#7.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(12.7.2)</A>, name Antioch in his list of Pisidian cities.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note94" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref94
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">94</A>
<I>i.e.</I> in the territory of which Antiocheia was capital. At this "remote old Anatolian Sanctuary" (not to be confused


<A ID="p433x"></A>with that of Mên Ascaeus near Antiocheia), "Strabo does not say what epithet Mên bore" (Ramsay in first article above cited). That of Mên Ascaeus on Mt. Kara Kuyu has been excavated by Ramsay and Calder (<I>J. H. S.</I> 1912, pp111‑150<!--</A>JOURNAL:JHS-->, <I>British School Annual</I> 1911‑12, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVIII</SPAN>.37 ff., <I>J. R. S.</I> 1918, pp107‑145<!--</A>JOURNAL:JRS-->). The other, not yet found, "may have been," according to Professor Robinson, "at Saghir."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note95" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref95
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">95</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "solemn processions."


