<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note107" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref107
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">107</A>
The translation conforms with a slight emendation of the Greek text. The <SPAN CLASS="small">MSS.</SPAN> make Strabo say that "Arsaces . . . was captured and slain by the sons of Pharnaces" (see critical note).

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify small italic">
The critical note to the Greek text (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">καὶ διεφθάρη εἰς τῶν Φαρνάκου τοῦ βασιλέως παίδων Ἀρσάκης</SPAN>) reads:
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ὑπό</SPAN>, Jones deletes, following J. A. R. Munro (<I>Hermathena</I>, — 1900), and Sir W. M. Ramsay (<I>Classical Review</I>, 1901, p54), the latter likewise conjecturing <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">εἶς</SPAN> for <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ὑπό</SPAN>.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note108" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref108
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">108</A>
<I>i.e.</I> as well as Zela and Megalopolis.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note109" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#ref109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">109</A>
Amaseia.


